****

Regarding CSS styles on generated HTML markup, you may want to rely on CSS's ability to target nested items, and apply a stylesheet to your document in the conventional manner. I found on occasion this was helped by the **html-classes** [extra](https://github.com/trentm/python-markdown2/wiki/Extras), but usually I wrapped the output in a container span or div, and applied an id or class to that container.

If you have some HTML output from your Python script such as this:

```HTML
<h1>Markdown example:</h1>
<div class="markdown-generated-output">
<h1>Hello!</h1>
<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur 
…
</div>
````

You could therefore apply styles with a stylesheet like this:

````CSS
h1 {
    color: black;
}
.markdown-generated-output {
    border: thin black solid;
    color: brown;
}
.markdown-generated-output h1 {
    color: red;
}
````

