@tacaswell In #135 you objected to bundling pytables into the conda package because you thought it conflicted with pytables. We have since figured out that it does not conflict anymore. That is,

    conda install h5py pytables

creates no problems. Are you OK with bundling pytables?

Though minor, removing these properties may be breaking for some users; ex. piping the results from `storage blob list` and doing a check on the properties returned. It also is reasonable to have similar models for the outputs of any iteration of the list command.
We have decided not to remove the null properties for now, if we get more complaints from users in the future, we will consider this further along the road. 
@bingosummer thanks for your input, glad I could help.

I solved my issue.

The problem was caused by differences between the files ~/.asound and /etc/asoundrc.

After I delete the file ~/.asoundrc and rebooted the volume of the Google Assistant was on the same high level as with With Alexa en aplay.

FYI I list the contents of both files:
```(env) pi@raspberrypi3:~ $ cat .asoundrc
pcm.!default {
 type asym
 capture.pcm "mic"
 playback.pcm "speaker"
}
pcm.mic {
 type plug
 slave {
 pcm "hw:1,0"
 }
}
pcm.speaker {
 type plug
 slave {
 pcm "hw:1,0"
 }
}

(env) pi@raspberrypi3:~ $ cat /etc/asound.conf 
# The IPC key of dmix or dsnoop plugin must be unique
# If 555555 or 666666 is used by other processes, use another one

pcm.!default {
    type asym
    playback.pcm "playback"
    capture.pcm "capture"
}

pcm.playback {
    type plug
    slave.pcm "dmixed"
}

pcm.capture {
    type plug
    slave.pcm "array"
}

pcm.dmixed {
    type dmix
    slave.pcm "hw:1,0"
    ipc_key 555555 
}

pcm.array {
    type dsnoop
    slave {
        pcm "hw:1,0"
        channels 2
    }
    ipc_key 666666
}

(env) pi@raspberrypi3:~ $ 
```

